\section{Abiotic Stress: A limit to Plant Productivity}
\label{sec:intro-stress}

Abiotic stresses are those applied to plants from their growth environment, including environmental
variables including temperature, humidity, salinity and water availability, and light quality and
quantity amongst many others. Salinity and drought stresses decrease a plant's ability to transpire
and obtain inorganic carbon vital to photosynthesis \autocite{seki_molecular_2003}. Excess light
creates harmful reactive oxygen species (ROS), and damages the photosynthetic aparatus
\autocite{niyogi_photoprotection_1999, asada_production_2006}. Extremes of temperature cause damage
to or non-optimal function of many enzymes, particularly those involved in metabolism
\autocite{atkin_thermal_2003}.  Together, abiotic stresses limit plant productivity as their
detrimental effects affect the ability of plants to assimilate biomass, and coping mechanisms plants
have evolved generally come at a yield penalty \autocite{mittler_abiotic_2006}. As a result,
enormous effort has been placed into the elucidation and improvement of these coping mechanisms,
however the study of stresses has not lead to the promised improved crops with as much success as
the effort to do so would justify.

