Plants respond to abiotic stress via a myriad of mechanisms
\autocite{demmig-adams_photoprotection_1992}, thus responses to abiotic stress must be studied via a
variety of techniques.  Studies of photosynthetic characteristics by chlorophyll fluorescence
\autocite{technical review} have illustrated the effects of abiotic stress of photosynthesis
\autocite{kulheim_rapid_2002, mishra_arabidopsis_2012, alter_acclimatory_2012,
tikkanen_regulation_2012}. Phenotypic analysis, particularly of plant morphology, has given insight
into the effects of abiotic stress \autocite{wituszynska_multivariate_2013,
armstrong_assessing_2007}. Studies of the transcriptome, or global cellular pool of expressed genes,
have provided insight into plant responses to many abiotic stresses and combinations thereof
\autocite{rossel_global_2002, kimura_identification_2003, seki_monitoring_2001,
atkinson_identification_2013}.

\subsection{Physiological Responses to Excess Light}
\label{subsec:intro-resp-physio}

Upon exposure to excess light, plants immediately  begin to mitigate its detrimental effects
\autocite{niyogi_photoprotection_1999, demmig-adams_photoprotection_1992}. These include
chloroplastic mechanisms discussed above (see \autoref{subsec:intro-stress-photodamage}) In addition
to these chloroplastic photoprotective mechanisms, plants can respond to excess light on a cellular
scale. Chloroplast avoidance movement, the movement of chloroplasts parallel to the incident angle
of light, decreases the amount of absorbed light \autocite{kasahara_chloroplast_2002}.
Transcriptional induction of heat shock proteins, antioxidant scavenging and Photooxidative damage
repair occur following excess light, and help to minimise oxidative damage
\autocite{niyogi_photoprotection_1999}. Production of anthocyanin, a protective class of pigments,
is induced by the production of reactive oxygen species due to excess light
\autocite{vanderauwera_genome-wide_2005}. Together, these responses serve to reduce the
Photooxidative damage of cells and tissues due to excess light.

